          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>In anterior dislocation of the temporomandibular joint, what prevents the condyle from returning to the mandibular fossa on its own?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>The articular disc blocks re-entry into the fossa</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Anterior disc displacement is a separate chronic TMJ disorder. It is not the mechanism that locks the condyle after acute anterior dislocation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The temporomandibular ligament becomes taut and holds the condyle forward</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The temporomandibular ligament limits posterior condyle movement. It does not hold the condyle in an anteriorly dislocated position.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The elevator muscles go into spasm, locking the condyle anterior to the tubercle</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct. The masseter, temporalis, and medial pterygoid go into reflex spasm after the condyle passes over the articular tubercle, preventing spontaneous reduction.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>The lateral pterygoid continues to pull the condyle forward</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>While the lateral pterygoid protrudes the mandible, the locked position is maintained by spasm of the elevator muscles, not by continued lateral pterygoid contraction.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "After the condyle slides anterior to the articular tubercle, the elevator muscles — masseter, temporalis, and medial pterygoid — go into reflex spasm and hold the condyle locked in the dislocated position. The Hippocratic manoeuvre overcomes this spasm by pushing the molars downward and backward."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Correct! The elevator muscles (masseter, temporalis, and medial pterygoid) go into spasm after the condyle clears the articular tubercle. The Hippocratic manoeuvre overcomes this by pushing the molars firmly downward and backward until the condyle returns to the fossa."
                }
              ],
